%N A389565 Total number of firings in a certain chip-firing game that starts with 2^n chips and is described in the comments.
%C A389565 Consider the following chip-firing game on the integer points of the first quadrant (i.e., set of vertices (x, y) where x and y are nonnegative integers): start with 2^n chips at the origin (i.e., point (0, 0)). If a vertex (x, y) has at least 2 chips, it fires by sending one chip to (x+1, y) and one chip to (x, y+1). The vertex (x, y) loses two chips during each firing. The total number of firings in the game is finite. a(n) is the total number of firings made in the game.
%H A389565 Ryota Inagaki, Tanya Khovanova, and Austin Luo, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.09125">Chip-firing on the Lattice of Nonnegative Integer Points</a>, arXiv:2601.09125 [math.CO], 2026. See p. 4.
%H A389565 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chip-firing_game">Chip-firing game</a>.
%H A389565 Andrei Zabolotskii, <a href="/A389565/a389565.png">The final configuration for n = 20</a> (the origin is at the top-left corner).
%e A389565 For n=2, we have a(2)=5 firings. We start with 4 chips at the origin. We fire the origin 2 times. This makes (1,0) and (0, 1) each have 2 chips. Both (1, 0) and (0, 1) fire once. Thus, (2, 0) gains 1 chip, (1, 1) gains 2 chips, and (0, 2) gains 1 chip. Vertex (1, 1) fires. Now, all vertices have either 0 or 1 chip. The chip-firing game has terminated. In total we have fired 2 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 5 times.
%o A389565 (Python)
%o A389565 def total_firings(n):
%o A389565     l1 = [2**n]
%o A389565     stab = (max(l1) <= 1)
%o A389565     fire_count=0
%o A389565     while not stab:
%o A389565         l2 = [l1[0]//2]
%o A389565         fire_count +=l1[0]//2
%o A389565         for i in range(1, len(l1)):
%o A389565             l2.append(l1[i]//2 + l1[i-1]//2)
%o A389565             fire_count += l1[i]//2
%o A389565         l2.append(l1[len(l1)-1]//2)
%o A389565         l1 = l2
%o A389565         stab = (max(l1) <= 1)
%o A389565         if l1[0] == 0:
%o A389565             l1 = l1[1:]
%o A389565         if l1[-1] == 0:
%o A389565             l1 = l1[:len(l1)-1]
%o A389565     return fire_count
%o A389565 sequence_total = ""
%o A389565 for n in range(26):
%o A389565     sequence_total = sequence_total + str(total_firings(n)) + ", "
%o A389565 print(sequence_total)
